[One cannot successfully double-guess a government committee, but the
indications to date are that they may come up with a recommendation for
vaccination & blood testing program with limited, ?one month,
quarantine/observation. Secondly, government is not responsible for the
health of individual dogs, only that any novel program allows the
introduction of the minimal number of "new" diseases and certainly never
rabies. On that scenario, (1) Babesiosis may be caught in the quarantine
kennel by an alert private vet; (2) Erhlichiosis ... it would be logical to
bathe/treat all incoming dogs with the appropriate acaricide if one does
not wish to repeat the US experience when they successfully introduced a
number of African tick species to various wildlife parks in spite of
"quarantine"; (3) ditto with appropriate heartworm treatments - the current
drugs are excellent; (4) for _E. multilocularis_ and _E.granulosus_ see:
Echinococcus, fox - Europe (03) 971206115307
Echinococcus, fox - Europe (04) 971221002056;
(5) because of the existing high cost of quarantine I doubt if that data
will reveal much here, but it might. Whether with the reduced cost and
inconvenience a new system will not only bring in an increased number of
dogs but also dogs from wider socio-economic and working-dog spectra that
before may be expected but who knows. I doubt if it is the dog that goes to
Berlin or Paris, or vice-versa to London or Edinburgh, with its family that
will pose a risk. The dog that goes camping is something else. - Mod.MHJ
......................................mhj/es
